7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.03089403-7357-4f00-b230-1d07123e99f3.description=
Copy files to and from remote machine through SSH.

Inputs\:
    host - IP address/host name.
    port - The port number to connect to.
    userName - Remote username.
    password - Password of user. If using a private key file this will be used as the passphrase for the file.
    localFile - Absolute path to the local file. This path is relative to the RAS host that the operation is running on.
    copyAction - To/From copy action.
Valid values\: to, from
    remoteFile - Absolute path to remote file.
    privateKeyFile - Absolute path for private key file for public/private key authentication.
 
Results\:
    returnResult - this is the primary output and contains a confirmation message if operation successfully completes, or an exception message otherwise.
    returnCode - it is 0 if operation successfully completes, -1 otherwise.
    exception - it contains an exception message if something went wrong.

Responses\: 
    success - The command was executed successfully file was copied.
    failure - The command could not be executed.

Examples\:
1. The following is a valid inputs example for copying a file from a Windows machine to a remote Linux machine\:
        host\: server2.example.com
        port\: 22
        userName\: username2
        password\: password2
        localFile\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        copyAction\: to
        remoteFile\: /root/example.txt
2. The following is a valid inputs example for copying a file from a remote Linux machine to a Windows machine\:
        host\: server2.example.com
        port\: 22
        userName\: username2
        password\: password2
        localFile\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        copyAction\: from
        remoteFile\: /root/example.txt
7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.175158a7-66ea-46bd-8e18-6be33e7fa17d.description=Creates a ZIP archive. Inputs\: zipFileName - The absolute path including file name of the ZIP archive to create. filesToAdd - Files to add to the ZIP archive. Can also be names of directories to be added. Could be added also wildcards like asterisk (*) or question mark (?). The asterisk (*) represents zero or more characters and question mark (?) represents a single character. Example\: The following path with wildcards "C\:\directory1\directory2\*.txt" will zip all files with ".txt" extensions recursively from "C\:\directory1\directory2" directory. addTopLevelDir - When adding a directory, indicates whether the directory itself should be added to the ZIP archive. Default value\: false Valid values\: true,false includeEmptyFolders - Specify whether to include empty folders into the final archive. Default value\: false Valid values\: true,false Responses\: success - The files were zipped successfully. failure - The files could not be zipped. Notes\: 1. If the zipFileName already exists the new provided directory/files for zipping will be added to the existing zip file. 7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.1ed4b23d-facc-4a80-b0e8-15fe33a8c171.description=Replaces a substring within a string.

7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.39352286-e597-4786-8533-43f8bb4364c5.description=Executes a Shell command(s) on the remote machine using the SSH protocol. Inputs\: host - The hostname/IP address of the remote machine. port - The port number for SSH protocol. Default value\: 22 username - Name of the account on the remote machine. password - The passwod for the username. If using a private key file, this will be used as the passphrase for the file. privateKeyFile - Path to private key file (OpenSSH type) on the machine where is the worker. knownHostsPolicy - The policy used for managing known_hosts file. We recommand to use a "strict" policy so as to verify the host key against a local file containing known, trustworthy machines. If you choose "allow" or "add" policy then you will connect to the server without any verification. If there is a Man-In-The-Middle attack then you will be connected to a fake server and the SSH commands that you send will go through that fake server. Valid values\: allow\=It will permit the connection to any hosts. strict\=It will permit the connection only to the hosts specified in known_hosts file. add\=It will permit the connection to any hosts, if the host is not in the known_hosts file it will be added. Default value\: strict command - The command(s) to execute. characterSet - The characterSet name for input stream encoding from the remote machine. Examples\: SJIS, EUC-JP, UTF-8 Default value\: UTF-8 pty - Whether to use a pseudo-terminal (PTY) session. Valid values\: false, true Default value\: false timeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete. Default value\: 90000 connectTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the connection to be made. Default value\: 10000 closeSession - If true it closes the SSH session at completion of this operation. If false the SSH session will be cached for future calls of this operation during the life of the flow. Valid values\: false, true Default value\: false useGlobalContext - Specifies whether to enable the session sharing into the subflows. Valid values\: false, true Default value\: false Results\: returnResult - The result of the command (STDOUT is success, otherwise STDERR). STDERR - The standard error of the command. STDOUT - The standard output of the command. exitStatus - The exit status of the remote command corresponding to the SSH channel. The exit status is only available for certain types of channels, and only after the channel was closed (more exactly, just before the channel is closed). Examples\: 0 for a successful command, -1 if the command was not yet terminated (or this channel type has no command), 126 if the command cannot execute. TimedOut - Is set to "true" if the value set in the "timeout" input has elapsed and the command timed out. Responses\: success - The command was executed successfully. failure - The command could not be executed or if the command was not yet terminated. Notes\: 1. If the SSH session is cached then only the connection is kept and not the context (variables) represented by SSH channel. 2. Hidden inputs\: knownHostsPath - Specifies the path to the known_hots file on the running server. Default value\: /.ssh/known_hosts Examples\: /home/admin/.ssh/known_hosts 3. In order to use private keys with different encryption types (ex.\: aes256-cbc) needs to be updated the /java/lib/security/local_policy.jar JAR file with one that accept all security policies (ex.\: http\://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html). After update you must restart the Studio or Central service. 4. The "timeout" input refers only to the command timeout and it's not linked with any kind of connection timeout. The "commandTimedOut" output shows if the command timed out and doesn't interfere with the returnResult, STDERR or STDOUT outputs, so even if the command times out these outputs will still be populated accordingly. 7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.538346c3-1849-4fce-8718-9a9eb749b805.description=Executes a Shell command(s) on the remote machine using the SSH protocol. 7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.6d180e27-3565-47bd-b8a5-bd722506269f.description=
This operation runs a SQL SELECT query.
The first row is returned on the first run of the operation.
Subsequent calls with the same information will return the other rows.

Inputs\:
    DBServerName - The hostname or ip address of the database server.
    DbType - The type of database to connect to. 
Valid values\: Oracle, MSSQL, Sybase, Netcool, DB2 and Custom.
Default value\: Oracle
    Username - The username to use when connecting to the server.
    Password - The password to use when connecting to the server.
    instance - The name instance of MSSQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance.
Example\: MSSQLSERVER
    DbPort - The port to connect to.
Valid values\: Oracle\: 1521, MSSQL\: 1433, Sybase\: 5000, Netcool\: 4100, DB2\: 50000.
    Database - The name of the database to connect to.
    authenticationType - The type of authentication used to access the database (applicable only to MSSQL type). 
Valid values\: sql, windows (for MSSQL)
default value\: sql
    dbClass - The class name of the JDBC driver to use.
    dbURL - The URL required to load up the driver and make your connection.
    Command - The SQL query to execute.
    Delimiter - The delimiter to use between resulted values in "returnResult" and column names in "columnNames".
    Key - The key to help keep multiple query results distinct.
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. When the default value is used, there is no limit on the amount of time allowed for a running command to complete.
Default values\: 0 
    databasePoolingProperties - Properties for database pooling configuration. This parameter replaces the databasePooling.properties file from 9x version (you may copy-paste the file content here). Pooling is disabled by default. For more details check the /Library/Operations/Database/JDBC folder description.
Example\: db.pooling.enable\=true
    resultSetType - the result set type. See JDBC folder description for more details.
Valid values\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY, TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE,TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE.
Default value\: TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE except DB2 which is overridden to TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY
    resultSetConcurrency - the result set concurrency. See JDBC folder description for more details.
Valid values\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY, CONCUR_UPDATABLE
Default value\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY
    ignoreCase - If set to true the inputs' letters case will be ignored and converted to lowercase.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the data of one row, separated by the "Delimiter". 
    columnNames - The names of all the columns returned, separated by the "Delimiter".
    rowsLeft - The number of remaining rows that match the query.

Responses\:
    more items - More rows are available for retrieval.
    no more items - No more rows are available.
    failure - Failed to execute the command.

Notes\: 
1. SQL statement other than SELECT statement (like INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE) is not supported. In case statements other than SELECT are executed then the operation will fail but the statements might get partially or fully executed in the database.
2. If the column type is "ntext", the "returnResult" returns the name of the JDBC driver instead of the actual column value. In this case, use the "SQL Query LOB" operation instead.

Note\:
    Check the JDBC folder description for details on how to load database connectors.
7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.6d5ed3a3-5119-4e5c-bddb-820e5a9c879a.description=
This operation writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file, append extra lines to it or even create a new file.

Inputs\:
    source -  Full path to file. If the file does not exist it is created first.
    contents - The content that should be written to the file. This input field can contain more lines, separated by a delimiter. If it contains the new line character (\n or \r\n), but this is not the delimiter, this character will be escaped and written to file.  
Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter.
    delimiter - Specifies the newline delimiter that is used to split the "contents" input field into separate lines that will be further written to the given file.
Examples\: \n, \r\n, etc
    characterSet - The character encoding used to write to the file. 
Default\: UTF-8. 
Valid values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE,  ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc.
    overwrite - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. 
Default\: true. 
Valid values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the "success" confirmation message if the operation successfully completes, or an exception message otherwise.
    returnCode - It has the value 0 if the operation successfully completes and 1 otherwise.
    exception - This contains an exception message if the operation fails.

Responses\:
    success - File/directory was written successfully.
    failure - Unable to write to file/directory, empty contents or source.

Examples\:
1. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Windows\:
    source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,

2. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Linux\:
    source\: /root/example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,
7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.831469fd-2baa-407c-b002-355e8275a450.description=
 Extract a ZIP archive.

Inputs\:

outputDirectory - Location where the extracted content to be written. If the directory doesn't exist, will be created.


Responses\:

failure - The files could not be extracted.

7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.ba348c88-a5f9-44c8-912e-f2d6d1586325.description=
This is a soft copy of 'Http Client' customized for the GET method (the input 'method'\='GET' should not be changed). Check the linked 'Http Client' operation.

Inputs
    url - The web address to make the request to. This must be a standard URL as specified in RFC 3986. This is a required input.
Format\: scheme\://domain\:port/path?query_string\#fragment_id
Examples\: https\://[fe80\:\:1260\:4bff\:fe49\:42fc]\:8080/my/path?key1\=val1&key2\=val2\#my_fragment
    authType - The type of authentication used by this operation when trying to execute the request on the target server. The authentication is not preemptive\: a plain request not including authentication info will be made and only when the server responds with a 'WWW-Authenticate' header the client will send required headers. If the server needs no authentication but you specify one in this input the request will work nevertheless. The client cannot choose the authentication method and there is no fallback so you have to know which one you need. If the web application and proxy use different authentication types, these must be specified like in the Example model. 
Default value\: basic
Valid values\: basic, digest, ntlm, kerberos, any, anonymous, "" or a list of valid values separated by comma.
Example\: basic,digest
    username - The user name used for authentication. For NTLM authentication, the required format is 'domain\user' and if you only specify the 'user' it will append a dot like '.\user' so that a local user on the target machine can be used. In order for all authentication schemes to work (except Kerberos) username is required.
    password - The password used for authentication.
    preemptiveAuth - If this field is 'true' authentication info will be sent in the first request. If this is 'false' a request with no authentication info will be made and if server responds with 401 and a header like WWW-Authenticate\: Basic realm\="myRealm" only then the authentication info will be sent.
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true, false
    proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the web site.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default value\: 8080. Valid values\: -1, and positive integer values. When the value is '-1' the default port of the scheme, specified in the 'proxyHost', will be used.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy. The 'authType' input will be used to choose authentication type. The 'Basic' and 'Digest' proxy auth type are supported.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value.
    trustAllRoots - Specifies whether to enable weak security over SSL/TSL. A certificate is trusted even if no trusted certification authority issued it.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    x509HostnameVerifier - Specifies the way the server hostname must match a domain name in the subject's Common Name (CN) or subjectAltName field of the X.509 certificate. The hostname verification system prevents communication with other hosts other than the ones you intended. This is done by checking that the hostname is in the subject alternative name extension of the certificate. This system is designed to ensure that, if an attacker(Man In The Middle) redirects traffic to his machine, the client will not accept the connection. If you set this input to "allow_all", this verification is ignored and you become vulnerable to security attacks. For the value "browser_compatible" the hostname verifier works the same way as Curl and Firefox. The hostname must match either the first CN, or any of the subject-alts. A wildcard can occur in the CN, and in any of the subject-alts. The only difference between "browser_compatible" and "strict" is that a wildcard (such as "*.foo.com") with "browser_compatible" matches all subdomains, including "a.b.foo.com". From the security perspective, to provide protection against possible Man-In-The-Middle attacks, we strongly recommend to use "strict" option.
Default value\: strict
Valid values\: strict, browser_compatible, allow_all
    trustKeystore - The pathname of the Java TrustStore file. This contains certificates from other parties that you expect to communicate with, or from Certificate Authorities that you trust to identify other parties.  If the protocol (specified by the 'url') is not 'https' or if trustAllRoots is 'true' this input is ignored.
Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
Format\: Java KeyStore (JKS)
    trustPassword - The password associated with the TrustStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and trustKeystore is empty, trustPassword default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    keystore - The pathname of the Java KeyStore file. You only need this if the server requires client authentication. If the protocol (specified by the 'url') is not 'https' or if trustAllRoots is 'true' this input is ignored.
Default value\: /java/lib/security/cacerts
Format\: Java KeyStore (JKS)
    keystorePassword - The password associated with the KeyStore file. If trustAllRoots is false and keystore is empty, keystorePassword default will be supplied.
Default value\: changeit
    connectTimeout - The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A timeout value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20
    socketTimeout - The timeout for waiting for data (a maximum period inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A socketTimeout value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
    useCookies - Specifies whether to enable cookie tracking or not. Cookies are stored between consecutive calls in a serializable session object therefore they will be available on a branch level (same subflow, same lane). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used.
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true,false
    keepAlive - Specifies whether to create a shared connection that will be used in subsequent calls. If keepAlive is false, the already open connection will be used and after execution it will close it. The operation will use a connection pool stored in a GlobalSessionObject that will be available throughout the execution (the flow and subflows, between parallel split lanes).
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true, false
    connectionsMaxPerRoute - The maximum limit of connections on a per route basis. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections per given route.
Default value\: 2
    connectionsMaxTotal - The maximum limit of connections in total. The default will create no more than 2 concurrent connections in total.
Default value\: 20
    followRedirects - Specifies whether the HTTP client automatically follows redirects.  Redirects explicitly prohibited by the HTTP specification as requiring user intervention will not be followed (redirects on POST and PUT requests that are converted to GET requests). If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used.
Default value\: true
Valid values\: true, false
    headers - The list containing the headers to use for the request separated by new line (CRLF).The header name - value pair will be separated by "\:".
Format\: Conforming with HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616).
Examples\: Accept\:text/plain
    destinationFile - The absolute path of a file on disk where to save the entity returned by the response. 'returnResult' will no longer be populated with the entity if this is specified. You should not use this for method\=HEAD or OPTIONS.	Example\: C\:\temp\destinationFile.txt
    responseCharacterSet - The character encoding to be used for the HTTP response. If responseCharacterSet is empty, the charset from the 'Content-Type' HTTP response header will be used. If responseCharacterSet is empty and the charset from the HTTP response Content-Type header is empty, the default value will be used. You should not use this for method\=HEAD or OPTIONS.
Default value\: ISO-8859-1
    queryParams - The list containing query parameters to append to the URL. The names and the values must not be URL encoded unless you specify "queryParamsAreURLEncoded"\=true because if they are encoded and "queryParamsAreURLEncoded"\=false they will get double encoded. The separator between name-value pairs is  "&". The query name will be separated from query value by "\=". Note that you need to URL encode at least "&" to "%26" and "\=" to "%3D" and set "queryParamsAreURLEncoded"\="true" if you leave the other special URL characters unencoded they will be encoded by the HTTP Client.
Examples\: parameterName1\=parameterValue1¶meterName2\=parameterValue2;
    queryParamsAreURLEncoded - Specifies whether to encode  (according to the url encoding standard) the queryParams. If you set "queryParamsAreURLEncoded"\=true and you have invalid characters in 'queryParams' they will get encoded anyway. If you specify a non-boolean value, the default value is used.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    queryParamsAreFormEncoded - Specifies whether to encode the queryParams in the the default format used by the apache http client library - form format. If this input is true then all characters will be encoded based on the queryParamsAreURLEncoded input.If queryParamsAreFormEncoded\=false all reserved chars are not encoded no matter of queryParamsAreURLEncoded input.The only exceptions are for space(' ')character which is encoded as %20 and + (plus) which is encoded as %20 and not encoded if queryParamsAreURLEncoded\=false. Check the "v2.0" folder description for more details.
Default value\: true. 
Valid values\: true, false
Example\: query\=test te%20@st will be encoded in query\=test%20te%20@st
    method - The HTTP method used. This is a required input.

Outputs
    returnResult - This will contain the response entity (unless 'destinationFile' is specified). In case of an error this output will contain the error message.
    exception - In case of success response, this result is empty. In case of failure response, this result contains the java stack trace of the runtime exception.
    statusCode - The HTTP status code.
Format\: 1xx (Informational - Request received, continuing process), 2xx (Success - The action was successfully received, understood, and accepted), 3xx (Redirection - Further action must be taken in order to complete the request), 4xx (Client Error - The request contains bad syntax or cannot be fulfilled), 5xx Server Error - The server failed to fulfil an apparently valid request)
Examples\: 200, 404
    finalLocation - The final location after redirects.
Format\: URL
    responseHeaders - The list containing the headers of the response message, separated by newline.
Format\: This is conforming with HTTP standard for headers (RFC 2616).
    protocolVersion - The HTTP protocol version.
Examples\: HTTP/1.1
    reasonPhrase - The reason phrase from the origin HTTP response. This depends on the status code and are according to RFC 1945 and RFC 2048
Examples\: (HTTP 1.0)\: OK, Created, Accepted, No Content, Moved Permanently, Moved Temporarily, Not Modified, Bad Request, Unauthorized, Forbidden, Not Found, Internal Server Error, Not Implemented, Bad Gateway, Service Unavailable	Values (HTTP 1.1)\: Continue, Temporary Redirect, Method Not Allowed, Conflict, Precondition Failed, Request Too Long, Request-URI Too Long, Unsupported Media Type, Multiple Choices, See Other, Use Proxy, Payment Required, Not Acceptable, Proxy Authentication Required, Request Timeout, Switching Protocols, Non Authoritative Information, Reset Content, Partial Content, Gateway Timeout, Http Version Not Supported, Gone, Length Required, Requested Range Not Satisfiable, Expectation Failed
    returnCode - The returnCode of the operation\: 0 for success, -1 for failure.

Responses
    success - The operation completed without a runtime exception. So it will go to success for any  http codes even those in the 400-599 range.
    failure - A runtime exception occurred. This may be due to incorrectly formated inputs (authType, contentType, headers, method, proxy, queryParams, requestCharacterSet, responseCharacterSet, truststore, url), or failed ntlm or Kerberos authentication.

Notes
Check the "v2.0" folder description for more help.
7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.c9d18063-b7ec-49cd-9f54-84ff385be80c.description=Executes a Shell command(s) on the remote machine using the SSH protocol. Inputs\: host - The hostname/IP address of the remote machine. port - The port number for SSH protocol. Default value\: 22 username - Name of the account on the remote machine. password - The passwod for the username. If using a private key file, this will be used as the passphrase for the file. privateKeyFile - Path to private key file (OpenSSH type) on the machine where is the worker. knownHostsPolicy - The policy used for managing known_hosts file. We recommand to use a "strict" policy so as to verify the host key against a local file containing known, trustworthy machines. If you choose "allow" or "add" policy then you will connect to the server without any verification. If there is a Man-In-The-Middle attack then you will be connected to a fake server and the SSH commands that you send will go through that fake server. Valid values\: allow\=It will permit the connection to any hosts. strict\=It will permit the connection only to the hosts specified in known_hosts file. add\=It will permit the connection to any hosts, if the host is not in the known_hosts file it will be added. Default value\: strict command - The command(s) to execute. characterSet - The characterSet name for input stream encoding from the remote machine. Examples\: SJIS, EUC-JP, UTF-8 Default value\: UTF-8 pty - Whether to use a pseudo-terminal (PTY) session. Valid values\: false, true Default value\: false timeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete. Default value\: 90000 connectTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the connection to be made. Default value\: 10000 closeSession - If true it closes the SSH session at completion of this operation. If false the SSH session will be cached for future calls of this operation during the life of the flow. Valid values\: false, true Default value\: false useGlobalContext - Specifies whether to enable the session sharing into the subflows. Valid values\: false, true Default value\: false Results\: returnResult - The result of the command (STDOUT is success, otherwise STDERR). STDERR - The standard error of the command. STDOUT - The standard output of the command. exitStatus - The exit status of the remote command corresponding to the SSH channel. The exit status is only available for certain types of channels, and only after the channel was closed (more exactly, just before the channel is closed). Examples\: 0 for a successful command, -1 if the command was not yet terminated (or this channel type has no command), 126 if the command cannot execute. TimedOut - Is set to "true" if the value set in the "timeout" input has elapsed and the command timed out. Responses\: success - The command was executed successfully. failure - The command could not be executed or if the command was not yet terminated. Notes\: 1. If the SSH session is cached then only the connection is kept and not the context (variables) represented by SSH channel. 2. Hidden inputs\: knownHostsPath - Specifies the path to the known_hots file on the running server. Default value\: /.ssh/known_hosts Examples\: /home/admin/.ssh/known_hosts 3. In order to use private keys with different encryption types (ex.\: aes256-cbc) needs to be updated the /java/lib/security/local_policy.jar JAR file with one that accept all security policies (ex.\: http\://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html). After update you must restart the Studio or Central service. 4. The "timeout" input refers only to the command timeout and it's not linked with any kind of connection timeout. The "commandTimedOut" output shows if the command timed out and doesn't interfere with the returnResult, STDERR or STDOUT outputs, so even if the command times out these outputs will still be populated accordingly. 7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.f1ae2200-105b-4fc9-8916-a7e968bd501e.description=Executes a Shell command(s) on the remote machine using the SSH protocol. The "commandTimedOut" output shows if the command timed out and doesn't interfere with the returnResult, STDERR or STDOUT outputs, so even if the command times out these outputs will still be populated accordingly. 7e9c50ce-9aac-4bf6-bc11-5009ff6ec5b8.f917783f-800b-4840-b00b-0c8d619f1cc6.description=
This operation reads the content of a file. The operation can be used to read the entire file content in one step or to iterate the file line by line.

Inputs\:
    source - The full path and filename of the file to be read. A UNC path can be supported as the source file path.
    filter - The string to filter on (leave blank for no filter). If this filter is not blank, all rows that contain the filter string will be returned. If no match is found, no lines will be returned.
    iterate - Determines whether the content of the file should be iterated or not. If set to "true", the content of the file will be iterated row by row and for each subsequent call, the next row will be returned. If set to "false", the content of the file will not be iterated and only the number of lines that matched the "filter" will be returned.
Valid values\: true, false
    delimiter – If specified, the entire content of the file  will be read, the specified value will be used as a delimiter between the rows and  the resulting content will be returned. If left blank, the next row will be returned for each subsequent call. 
    eofReset - If set to true, after the No More response has been returned once, the operation will restart reading the file from the beginning on the next call.
Valid values\: true, false
    characterSet - The character set of the file to read from. For invalid or empty input value the default encoding will be used. 
Valid values\: UTF-8, UTF-16 and UTF-32 
Default value\: UTF-8

Results\:
    returnCode - This is the primary output. It is 0 if the operation completed successfully  (or if more rows are available when iterate is set to true), 1 if no more items (if iterate is set to true) and -1 in case of failure. 
    count - The number of lines that matched the filter, or if no filter specified, the total lines read (if iterate is false, or delimiter is not null). Otherwise, it returns the number of rows available for retrieval from the source file.
    returnResult - Each row by turn (if iterate is true and delimiter is blank) or all rows separated by the delimiter (if iterate is true and delimiter is not blank).
    exception - An exception message if the operation fails.

Responses\:
    success - The operation successfully read the file (if iterate is true, more rows are available).
    no more items - No more items are available for retrieval (if iterate is set to true).
    failure - The operation failed to read the file.

Notes\:
1. The "filter" and "eofReset" fields are taken into consideration only if iterate is set to true. Otherwise, they have no impact on the result.
2. Note that the "filter" match is not performed based on a regular expression, although the filter field may contain one. The operation only checks for each row if it contains the string given as filter. 
3. If i"terate" is set to "true" and "delimiter" is not null, the entire file may or may not still be fully read at once, depending on size. 
4. If "iterate" is set to "true", then all matching lines are pushed into the Session and then, subsequent calls to the operation, result in the next line being returned.
5. If the value provided in the "delimiter" field is not null, the entire file will be read once and returned regardless of the value of the "iterate" field.

Examples\:
    The following examples are used to illustrate the behavior of the operation for three specific use cases. For these examples, the operation will use as the input source a file called "example.txt", with the absolute path "C\:\Program Files\example.txt" and the following content\:
        "line1
         line2
         line3
         line4"
1. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "true" and the "delimiter" input field is not left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: true
        delimiter\: ,
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will have the following value\: line1,line2,line3,line4
2. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "true" and the delimiter input field is left blank\:
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: true
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the file will be iterated row by row in four subsequent calls. At each call, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will contain the value of one line from the file, in the same order as they are found in the source file (i.e. line1, line2, lin3, line4). 
3. This is a valid inputs example for reading the content of a file, when the "iterate" input field is set to "false" and the "delimiter" input field is left blank\:       
        source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
        filter\:
        iterate\: false
        delimiter\:
        eofReset\: false
        characterSet\: UTF-8
    In this case, the "returnResult" output field of the operation will be blank and the count output field will contain the value 4 (representing the number of lines in the file).
